. To those who still do not get the idea yet:
You debug the following virtualized program:
```
function main() // <-breakpoint1
{
subroutine_1();
if(condition)
subroutine_2();
else
subroutine_3();
subroutine_4();
}
function subroutine_1() // <-breakpoint2
{
subroutine_5();
}
function subroutine_2() // <-breakpoint3
{
}
function subroutine_3() // <-breakpoint4
{
subroutine_5();
}
function subroutine_4() // <-breakpoint5
{
subroutine_5();
}
function subroutine_5() // <-breakpoint6
{
}
function subroutine_6() // <-breakpoint7
{
}
```
You run main() four times, then you probably get the hit counters:
breakpoint1 : 4
breakpoint2 : 4
breakpoint3 : 3
breakpoint4 : 1
breakpoint5 : 4
breakpoint6 : 9
breakpoint7 : 0
We can guess the probable control flow. There are many breakpoints executed 4 times, so these breakpoints are executed sequentially probably. And we can see breakpoint3+breakpoint4 is 4 times, so it is possible that they are a pair of statements in a "if-else" statement. breakpoint6 is executed 9 times, and 9=4+4+1, so it is possible that breakpoint6 is executed twice in the main control flow, and executed once more in subroutine_3. breakpoint7 is not executed, so it is not in the control flow. A possible graph is given below:
breakpoint6 -> (breakpoint1->breakpoint3+breakpoint4)+breakpoint2+breakpoint4
Under pratical condition, it is usually the case the graph must have many roots, because there is no subroutine that is called in all control flow branches. Nodes with zero hit count can be ignored. Nodes with equal hit count can be assumed to be executed one after another, so they can be graphed as a list instead of a tree. A node cannot be the child of itself. Child node may be used many times because it is possible to call the same subroutine many times.
The graph should be read bottom-up. The least executed functions are the main control flow. Then they calls their parents, then the parents call their parents. The root is the most frequently called subroutine.
