. # Usages of event counters:
1. As a general purpose counter: When there are many events bursting out in a second, you can count it with events counter.
   When the program starts you may notice there are many debug events. Most of these events are DLL load events. If the program loads within one or two seconds, you can directly watch the events counter and roughly know how many DLLs the program uses. Similarly, if the program outputs some debug strings, you can count the number of strings from the event counter. This usage requires an exact counter.
2. As a tool to watch the state of the program: Well-designed "animate into" operation should maintain a very steady stepping rate. If there are any extra debug events, you know something unexpected is happening, and probably stop stepping immediately. This usage does not require an exact counter.
