I can't see anything wrong with the TE code per se, but that's mostly because it's doing so much unnecessary work that it's hard to make out what is really going on. But it also doesn't help that the AVX/XSTATE API in Windows is nearly nonexistent apart from a single 10 year old MSDN page.
It seems to me that for this specific case (setting a single value, or even setting ymm0-ymm15 all at once) there should be no need to call both GetThreadContext and SetThreadContext more than once each. I get that SetContextDataEx is supposed to be a generic multipurpose function, but this is still something that reeks strongly of doing it wrong to me. Not that I have any better suggestions at the moment - I'll have to read up on the XSTATE API (or lack thereof). And you'll be hearing from my lawyer about that 6700K.. It is definitely possible that it is an Intel specific bug. Using AVX correctly (meaning, making your code faster with it, and not slower) on Intel CPUs is actually pretty difficult for a bunch of reasons:
- Mixing legacy SSE code and 256/512 bit AVX instructions has a severe performance penalty on mainstream Intel CPUs (Sandy Bridge, Ivy Bridge, Haswell, Broadwell) because the CPU needs to switch the register file to a different state (a complete tragic description of these states and their transitions can be found in 13.2 of Agner Fog's optimization guide). The movd xmm1, eax in the OP is an example where this would happen. Changing this to vmovd would significantly improve performance if this was some performance critical piece of code, for no obvious reason at all to the programmer. But wait! There's a simple fix! If you simply issue vzeroupper or vzeroall after finishing AVX execution, the penalty won't be incurred. But wait! On the Knight's Landing platform these instructions cost 36 clock cycles, so definitely don't do it there. On Skylake on the other hand it is not costly, but neither is the SSE/AVX transition anymore. So you can skip it on Skylake if you want. Simple stuff right?
- In order to save power, CPUs that support 256 or 512 bit operations actually run at half of their potential most of the time by turning off the upper execution unit bits, so a 256 bit operation will become two sequential 128 bit operations, making AVX much slower. This penalty goes away after a 'warm up' period, after which the CPU decides that hey, maybe this guy actually really needs the performance, and it enables full 256/512 bit operations for a while.
- In kernel mode, you have to manually XSAVE before starting any AVX execution and XRESTOR afterwards, in order not to automatically zero the upper part of future expansions to AVX, like the zmm registers that were added in AVX512. This alone makes it hardly worth it to even bother at all. This is not specific to Intel by the way, but it does suck.
- Unaligned memory access (vmovups) is much slower than aligned access (vmovaps) on pre-Nehalem CPUs, but there is almost no difference between the two on newer architectures.
- 'AVX512' is not really actually a thing, because it consists of many subsets of loosely related instructions that are all supported by some CPU, but no CPU supports all of them. Quoting Agner Fog again (13.3, emphasis mine):

There are several additional extensions to AVX512. All processors with AVX512 have some
of these extensions, but no processor so far has them all (writing in 2018). The known and
planned extensions to AVX512 are the following:
 - AVX512F. Foundation. All AVX512 processors have this. Includes operations on 32-
bit and 64-bit integers, float and double in 512-bit vectors, including masked
operations.
 - AVX512VL. Includes the same operations on 128-bit and 256-bit vectors, including
masked operations and 32 vector registers.
 - AVX512BW. Operations on 8-bit and 16-bit integers in 512-bit vectors.
 - AVX512DQ. Multiplication and conversion instructions with 64-bit integers. Various
other instructions on float and double.
 - AVX512ER. Fast reciprocal, reciprocal square root, and exponential function.
Precise on float; approximate on double.
 - AVX512CD. Conflict detection. Find duplicate elements in a vector.
 - AVX512PF. Prefetch instructions with gather/scatter logic.
 - AVX512VBMI. Permutation and shift with 8-bit granularity.
 - AVX512IFMA. Fused multiply-and-add on 52-bit integers.
 - AVX512_4VNNIW. Iterated dot product on 16-bit integers.
 - AVX512_4FMAPS. Iterated fused multiply-and-add, single precision

