Re: RtlpQueryProcessDebugInformationRemote and pausing: I know ntdll expressly creates this thread using NtCreateThreadEx with THREAD_CREATE_FLAGS_HIDE_FROM_DEBUGGER set in order to prevent these kinds of issues. Whether that is enough to prevent all problems I don't know. I recall at least one instance when I found out a program was deadlocked because of an RtlQueryProcessDebugInformation call that was issued by another process.. Yes, that's what I thought as well. THREAD_CREATE_FLAGS_HIDE_FROM_DEBUGGER is very powerful, to the point where a thread with the flag set may even be ignored when a process suspend is issued (though don't quote me on this), but it's not enough to start execution in a process that's already suspended, which would be the case here. I know because I wrote an implementation of NtCreateThreadEx for the XP kernel once, ironically with the purpose of banning this flag altogether as a ScyllaHide-type hook, and I ended up having to special-case the ntdll debug heap query thread to essentially give it godmode powers to prevent issues with suspended threads. (and processes, which from the kernel's POV are nothing more than processes containing only suspended threads, though it may lie and say each thread's individual suspend count is 0).
There's no reason why RtlpQueryProcessDebugInformationRemote couldn't be implemented out-of-process using ReadProcessMemory however. You'd simply have to calculate the offsets, basically like the guy in the blog already did minus the crash, and then issue a ReadProcessMemory for each individual node and block. It would be slower, but not by that much; NtReadVirtualMemory is very fast (it doesn't really care if the virtual address you're reading is in your own process or another one after it has performed the access checks). This would allow doing the enumeration in the debugger while the debuggee is suspended. It might be preferable to do it this way regardless since it removes the dependency on the ntdll imports. You'd still be reliant on the undocumented heap node structure layout, but that struct hasn't been changed in a looong time. I'm not saying I have a copy of the leaked NT4 source from 1995 because that would be illegal, but if I did, I might find the exact same struct as the one linked above in there.. Sure. A ProcessHeap in the PEB is what's returned from RtlCreateHeap:
