I have sort of lost hope that #1463 will ever become a reality, at least for launching regular console/GUI processes. The problem is that other than creating the kernel process and initial thread, CreateProcess is also responsible for notifying the session's csrss.exe of the new process. This is done through an LPC request (additionally accompanied by an array of pointers that has to be allocated in a shared section) containing three different flags fields, a handle to the file backing the newly created process, all sorts of details such as the machine type and PEB address (two in the case of WoW64) that CSRSS could easily query for itself, and even inane stuff like the VA and size of the manifest if one is present, because SxS runs inside CSRSS! If you get even a single part of this wrong you simply receive an error status like STATUS_INVALID_PARAMETER, and good luck debugging it because attaching a debugger to your session's CSRSS locks up the system.
Despite all this I do actually have code that can start regular processes this way on Windows 7/8/10, but not on XP and only on x64, and Jupiter probably has to be in the right phase too or something. Since MS seems to change the size and layout of the message struct with every OS update as well, maintaining all this would be a nightmare.
Note that all of this only relates to telling CSRSS about the process. The actual process and thread creation part is (relatively) easy, and CSRSS doesn't need to be aware of a process for it to be able to run. The process will be heavily restricted in what it can do though, because any sort of user interaction (mouse/keyboard input, creating a console, showing anything on the screen...) requires a connection to the CSRSS LPC port. Thus you would be limited to DbgPrint or else something like named pipes for IPC to communicate with the outside world.
The function I added to TitanEngine is a lot more modest; in fact it has exactly the same signature as InitDebugW. The idea is that it can be used as a drop-in replacement for InitDebugW when CreateProcess fails, to retry the process create. Something like:
C++
if ((processInfo = InitDebugW(path, cmdLine, dir)) == NULL)
{
  // check if the error matches known BS ones from CreateProcess, and if so, retry
  if (isBogusStatus(GetLastError())
    processInfo = InitNonWin32DebugW(path, cmdLine, dir);
}
This sidesteps the CSRSS problem (which isn't very relevant here, because CSRSS actually checks the subsystem anyway and rejects the connection if the process isn't CLI or GUI), while still allowing starting and debugging processes of any subsystem type.. I've created a PR in the TitanEngine repository to add the above API: https://bitbucket.org/titanengineupdate/titanengine-update/pull-requests/12
