If the call fails, we can filter by error code. GetLastError() results from CreateProcess can be divided into two categories: bullshit and non-bullshit. Non-bullshit errors are real errors returned by the kernel (meaning NtCreateUserProcess fails, e.g. when you try to create a protected process from a non-protected process). Bullshit errors are all errors set by kernel32 for some other reason after the process has already been successfully created. After setting such an error, kernel32 terminates the process and makes it look like it was never there.
Incomplete list of bullshit errors:
- ERROR_ACCESS_DENIED Most likely a real error, but can be a process create deny from either one of the hilariously dumb "AppCertDlls" or "WinSafer" checks (which can be caused by malware)
- ERROR_GEN_FAILURE Possible return value of "AppCertDlls" check if the check itself fails. Yes really.
- ERROR_NO_MORE_FILES I don't even know how this happens
- ERROR_PROC_NOT_FOUND Misleading - comes from "BasepCheckWinSaferRestrictions" and doesn't have anything to do with missing imports
- ERROR_CHILD_NOT_COMPLETE Subsystem not CLI/GUI
- ERROR_BAD_EXE_FORMAT Image version mismatch, or the file is a DLL. Can also be a legitimately invalid exe of course
- ERROR_CANCELLED VERY misleading error set if "BasepCheckBadapp" returns STATUS_ACCESS_DENIED. Almost seems to be on purpose
- ERROR_ACCESS_DISABLED_WEBBLADE Hilariously bad security check done in user mode after the process has already been created
- ERROR_ACCESS_DISABLED_WEBBLADE_TAMPER Variant of same
SxS bullshit errors:
- ERROR_FILENAME_EXCED_RANGE [sic]
- ERROR_RESOURCE_DATA_NOT_FOUND
- ERROR_RESOURCE_TYPE_NOT_FOUND
- ERROR_RESOURCE_NAME_NOT_FOUND
- ERROR_RESOURCE_LANG_NOT_FOUND
- ERROR_MUI_FILE_NOT_FOUND
- The entire ERROR_SXS_* range (>= 14000, <= 14110)
There is one exception: ERROR_ELEVATION_REQUIRED really means what it says and using NtCreateUserProcess won't help. I think the reason this error isn't returned by the kernel is because it requires parsing the XML manifest.
Unfortunately as you can see the intersection of the sets of real and bullshit errors is non-zero (especially ERROR_ACCESS_DENIED is likely to be real). But in most cases this should be accurate.
If the error code is one of the above, we can log the first error and retry the process create attempt with InitNativeDebugW. If that fails too, the error was real so no need to log it again. If it succeeds, we should probably add a warning to the log that the process was created natively and that it may have unexpected issues or just not run at all.. Re: DLL debugging: there is something to be said for using NtCreateUserProcess for DLL debugging instead of the current loader behaviour. This way the process is actually the DLL and not a container. However this would require changing the entry point, since DLLs normally expect to start in
