There are a few APIs that do similar-ish but not exactly the same things that can be used to change DLL load behaviour:
- SetDefaultDllDirectories - it's recommended to call this with LOAD_LIBRARY_SEARCH_SYSTEM32 only in order to prevent DLL preloading attacks, however you need to call LoadLibraryEx with the correct flags to override the search path after this for any DLLs/plugins in the x64dbg dir and the plugins subdir. This entire function and the LoadLibraryEx flags LOAD_LIBRARY_SEARCH_SYSTEM32, LOAD_LIBRARY_SEARCH_USER_DIRS and others are not supported on XP. So this one is probably N/A for now.
- AddDllDirectory/RemoveDllDirectory: similar, you need to call LoadLibraryEx with LOAD_LIBRARY_SEARCH_USER_DIRS for this to work and neither of these function exists on XP. This is a shame because it seems like the best option to me (add the x64dbg directory, and then add the plugins directory).
- SetSearchPathMode: this actually only affects SearchPath and the flags are pretty useless (disable, enable or enable | permanent). Windows 7 required, or KB959426 on XP/2003/Vista.
- SetDllDirectory: same as Add/RemoveDllDirectory, except this only supports one DLL directory. If you set a directory using this, it disables safe DLL search mode for the duration. You can remove the directory again by calling SetDllDirectory(L""), or restore the default search order with SetDllDirectory(NULL). Erm... interesting API design? I'm pretty sure the second is the correct choice since it seems like the only way to restore safe DLL search mode. Despite only supporting one directory it does seem like this should work since the application directory is added to the DLL search path too regardless of the current directory.
