webro666:
Since I've always worked with msdia instead of dbghelp, I just ran some tests and observed the following with dbghelp (at least on my system):
calling SymSetOptions without SYMOPT_UNDNAME will make undecorated names unavailable, no matter what. UnDecorateSymbolName will not give you any undecorated names.
calling SymSetOptions with SYMOPT_UNDNAME will undecorate all names automatically (decorated names will be lost). No need to call UnDecorateSymbolName in this case.
MSDN also states: "To use undecorated symbols, call the SymSetOptions function with the SYMOPT_UNDNAME option."
So, whatever is going on here, UnDecorateSymbolName is completely useless. If you specify SYMOPT_UNDNAME, you get undecorated symbols by default (meaning, you don't have to call it to get the undecorated name), if you don't specify SYMOPT_UNDNAME it will simply do nothing.
And about the exports problem, I observed the following:
If you let dbghelp find the corresponding .pdb file, it will just read symbols out of the pdb file and totally ignore the export table in the corresponding module. So if the .pdb file does not have export table symbols, you won't get any export table symbols.
If you don't let dbghelp find the .pdb file, it will read imports and exports from the module.
So, to fix undecorated symbols, you would probably have to specify SYMOPT_UNDNAME within SymSetOptions (if undecoration is set in engine options).
And to fix the exports problem, you would have to manually extract information from the export table in addition to getting symbols from dbghelp, if the .pdb does not store any export information.
I'm not sure, if I'm the only one with this strange behaviour..
. I've also done some more experimenting. I downloaded the latest debugging tools, copied all related files to the x64dbg directory where the exe resides, but I can't get undecorating to work. Public symbols in the form of _SymbolName@XX will not get undecorated without specifying SYMOPT_UNDNAME, no matter what params I specify in UnDecorateSymbolName. But that's not too big of a deal, because I will just go ahead and specify SYMOPT_UNDNAME and take the loss of decorated names.
But the fact, that exported api functions are not displayed in the CPU and Symbols windows is really kind of annoying.
So I tried to get a quick "hacky" workaround going like this:
In symbolinfo.cpp add the line
SymEnumExports(Base, EnumCallback, UserData);
to the end of the SymEnum function.
SymEnumExports looks like this (as I said, just a quick "hacky" version):
void SymEnumExports(duint Base, CBSYMBOLENUM EnumCallback, void* UserData)
{
SYMBOLINFO symbol;
memset(&symbol, 0, sizeof(SYMBOLINFO));
symbol.isImported = false;
apienumexports(Base, [&](duint base, const char *mod, const char* name, duint addr)
{
symbol.addr = addr;
symbol.decoratedSymbol = (char *)name;
symbol.undecoratedSymbol = (char *)name;
EnumCallback(&symbol, UserData);
});
}
It now shows exported functions in the Symbols window, but the CPU window still doesn't recognize exports :(
